        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>For our galaxy redshifts, the CO(4-3) line falls in the ALMA bands 6 .  

Configuration: Our project is based on the detection of the line and its integrated flux, therefore we require high sensitivity and the compact configuration with spatial resolution 1.7 arcsec, well suited for the size of our galaxies (~ 2 to 5 arcsec).  Besides measuring the gas velocity dispersion (expected to increase with redshift), by detecting the line emission barycenters in the channel maps, we shall nevertheless be able to resolve the velocity gradients and to derive rotation curves, as well as identify possible perturbations due to mergers.


Sensitivity and signal-to-noise ratio: We estimated the exposure
times on very conservative grounds, aiming at signal-to-noise ratios ~5 to ~10 achieved with a 0.5mJy rms in the 12CO(4-3) line and a 30km/s sensitivity.  This secures a highly significant detection of the CO emission in all galaxies leading to
accurate estimates of their gas content.

Number of pointings: We divided our sample in 2 science goals, each one corresponding to one frequency tuning.  We need 7 pointings for 8 galaxies in total in this science goal, indeed two galaxies will fall within the ALMA primary beam.

For the detection of the CO lines, we use the 1875MHz bandwidths with spectral average of 16 for a final resolution of $\sim$9km/s. Our primary target is the 12CO(4-3) which falls around 271GHz at the redshift of CL1054-11.  Our set-up is also tunned to enable the possible detection of 13CO(4-3) in the LSB around 259GHz. A 2000MHz continuum windows was placed in each of the LSB and USB  a in order to possibly  measure the dust content of our targets.

Exposure time: Following Solomon &amp; Vanden Bout (2005, ARAA,
43,677), we first derived the integrated line intensity L'CO of our
targets, from which we then estimated the observed fluxes, SCO, considering a line FWHM of 300km/s.  Moreover we applied a correction to the CO luminosities taking into account the difference in the Rayleigh-Jeans brightness temperature of the
higher J transitions than C(0-1).  We took L'[CO(4-3)]/L'[CO(1-0)] = 0.4 (e.g., Papadopoulos et al., 2007, ApJ, 668, 815; Weiss et al, 2007, A&amp;A 467, 955).  The FIR luminosities, redshifts of the sources, and expected fluxes in CO(4-3) line are listed in Table 1.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
