    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>There is clear evidence that the cold gas fueling star formation in galaxies can be altered in dense environments. Nevertheless, the origin and the operating modes of this depletion remains to be understood. Thanks to ALMA it is now possible to make substantial progress on this question and to obtain, at a redshift which is simply not accessible with other existing instrumentation, a direct view on how and where galaxies modify their reservoir of molecular gas as they fall into the inner regions of a given cluster. This piece of information is currently dramatically missing.

We propose to provide the first measurements of the cold molecular gas content of 9 LIRGs located at cluster-centric distances ranging from ~3R200 to 0.2R200, fully probing the regions of interest: from the furthest distances at which the cluster environment starts to affect the galaxy star formation history to the inner most regions, in a z=0.6972 medium mass cluster.
</prp:abstract>
